
<section class="row">
  <article class="col">
    <h1 class="display-4">Vegetation Types</h1>
    <p class="lead">The Hex River Valley is a floral transition zone between Fynbos, Renosterveld
    and Karoo vegetation types. It is also a geological transition zone between the Cape Fold
    Mountains and the buttes (koppies) and mesas (table-like hills) of the Karoo.</p>

    <div class="row wx-auto row-cols-1 row-cols-sm-3">
      <figure class="figure col">
        <img src="<%= Routes.static_url(@conn, "/images/fynbos.jpg") %>" class="figure-img img-thumbnail" alt="Fynbos">
        <figcaption class="figure-caption">A <b>Fynbos</b> landscape, featuring a common sunshine conebush (<i>Leucadendron salignum</i>).</figcaption>
      </figure>

      <figure class="figure col">
        <img src="<%= Routes.static_url(@conn, "/images/renosterveld.jpg") %>" class="figure-img img-thumbnail" alt="Fynbos">
        <figcaption class="figure-caption">A <b>Renosterveld</b> landscape, featuring a renosterbos (<i>Dicerothamnus rhinocerotis</i>).</figcaption>
      </figure>

      <figure class="figure col">
        <img src="<%= Routes.static_url(@conn, "/images/robertson_karoo.jpg") %>" class="figure-img img-thumbnail" alt="Karoo">
        <figcaption class="figure-caption">A <b>Karoo</b> landscape, featuring a botterboom (<i>Tylecodon paniculatus</i>).</figcaption>
      </figure>
    </div>

    <h3>Fynbos</h3>

    <p>Fynbos is a biome that is endemic to the Cape region. The word literally translates to "fine bush". Fynbos
    species tend to be highly specialized and adapted to their habitats. They thrive in sandy, nutrient-poor,
    acidic soils (hence the local name "Suurveld" or acidic field), and occur in winter rainfall areas. They are extremely
    well-adapted to the dry hot summer months. They often have small, hairy leaves that allow them to reflect the sun and
    minimize water loss. Many Fynbos species rely on fire to stimulate germination. Ants also play an important role in depositing seeds
    underground.</p>

    <h3>Renosterveld</h3>

    <p>Renosterveld is a vegetation type that is strictly part of the Fynbos biome, but prefers more nutrient rich, loamy
    soils and therefore lacks several characteristic Fynbos species such as proteas, heaths, restios, and hardleaves. Instead,
    Renosterveld is dominated by the renosterbos, a hardy pale unpalatable shrub. Other notable species such as snowbushes,
    karees, sand olives, and tentfigs, some of which also occur in Fynbos, accompany the renosterbos.</p>

    <h3>Karoo</h3>

    <p>The De Doorns Karoo (often in a mosaic with Renosterveld) is a vegetation type of the Succulent Karoo biome. It is sometimes
    treated as synonymous with Worcester Karoo or Robertson Karoo and is endemic to the Breede River Valley. It is a winter rainfall
    area on the rain shadow side of the Hex River Mountains receiving much less rain than Fynbos. The area is rich in succulents (aloes,
    spurges, butterbushes, babboon cabbages, succulent geraniums), geophytes (numerous bulbous and cormous species), seasonal undergrowth
    (daisies), and Karoobossies (kraalbushes, gumbushes and snowbushes).</p>

    <h3>Vegetation types</h3>

    <p>The broad Fynbos, Renosterveld, and Karoo themes are further broken down into vegetation types, a dozen or so of which flow together
    in the Hex River Valley.</p>

      <div class="row wx-auto row-cols-1 row-cols-sm-1">
      <figure class="figure col">
        <img src="<%= Routes.static_url(@conn, "/images/hex_veg.jpg") %>" class="figure-img img-thumbnail" alt="Vegetation type map">
        <figcaption class="figure-caption">A map of the Hex River Valley with vegetation types overlaid. Source: Helme, N. A. 2007.</figcaption>
      </figure>
    </div>

    <div class="album py-5">
      <div class="row row-cols-1 row-cols-sm-2 row-cols-md-4 g-4">
        <%= for vegetation_type <- @vegetation_types do %>
        <div class="col">
          <div class="card shadow-sm h-100">
            <%=if vegetation_type.has_image? do %><img src="<%= Routes.static_url(@conn, "/images/" <> vegetation_type.id <> ".jpg") %>" alt="<%= vegetation_type.name %>"><% end %>

            <div class="card-body">
              <h5 class="card-title">
                <%= link vegetation_type.name, to: Routes.vegetation_type_path(@conn, :show, vegetation_type)%>
              </h5>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <% end %>
      </div>
    </div>

